00:25:23.396 --> 00:25:24.731
Abercrombie came to me

460
00:25:24.814 --> 00:25:27.859
and asked me to create the murals
for the Abercrombie stores.

461
00:25:30.987 --> 00:25:35.283
These homoerotic but beautiful guys
interacting with each other.

462
00:25:36.868 --> 00:25:41.540
They make you think about the eternal
and that everything is forever good.

463
00:25:45.544 --> 00:25:46.461
Take one. Mark.

464
00:25:50.465 --> 00:25:52.467
So I'm the armpit guy.

465
00:25:54.094 --> 00:25:57.556
Abercrombie found a niche
with finding brand new models.

466
00:25:57.639 --> 00:25:59.349
Middle America.

467
00:25:59.432 --> 00:26:01.351
big. strong. like. dudes.

468
00:26:01.434 --> 00:26:03.645
And I was like…
[mimics accent] "Oh yeah. don't you know.

469
00:26:03.728 --> 00:26:06.147
I'm. like. here from Minnesota
for my modeling."

470
00:26:07.649 --> 00:26:11.403
I guess I looked like what they kind of
were always puttin' out there.

471
00:26:12.153 --> 00:26:13.738
I'm from Nebraska.

472
00:26:13.822 --> 00:26:16.616
I was captain of the football team.
of the wrestling team.

473
00:26:16.700 --> 00:26:19.077
homecoming king. all that kind of stuff.

474
00:26:19.911 --> 00:26:23.081
It wasn't. like. a big dream of mine
to be an Abercrombie model.

475
00:26:23.790 --> 00:26:26.001
I was drunk in a bar. and some lady--

476
00:26:26.084 --> 00:26:29.963
some gal that was apparently
a scout for Abercrombie was like. um.

477
00:26:30.046 --> 00:26:32.465
"Will you come into the store tomorrow?
You have a great look."

478
00:26:33.800 --> 00:26:35.302
We took a couple Polaroids.

479
00:26:35.385 --> 00:26:37.470
and then three weeks later.
I was in Brazil.

480
00:26:38.263 --> 00:26:41.975
That was the first time I saw the ocean
and traveled outside of Nebraska.

481
00:26:44.394 --> 00:26:48.064
People on crew would just insinuate
to just be yourself. be original.

482
00:26:48.148 --> 00:26:49.733
just do whatever.

483
00:26:49.816 --> 00:26:52.068
You know. climb trees. jump in water.

484
00:26:52.652 --> 00:26:55.488
Bruce. if you caught his eye
doing something natural.

485
00:26:56.031 --> 00:26:57.699
interacting with the wilderness.

486
00:26:57.782 --> 00:27:00.452
that would be a good way
to get your picture taken.

487
00:27:00.952 --> 00:27:02.704
There would just be guys in a tree.

488
00:27:02.787 --> 00:27:06.458
just like. "Hey. Bruce!
It's a tree. and I'm in it."

489
00:27:06.541 --> 00:27:09.836
Or just. like. doing push-ups on a curb.

490
00:27:09.919 --> 00:27:13.131
The guys were so testosteroney
'cause it's a bunch of ripped dudes.

491
00:27:13.214 --> 00:27:15.759
And then the guys
are trying to impress the women.

492
00:27:15.842 --> 00:27:18.845
It's really… It's just. like.
humanity at its basic level.

493
00:27:23.933 --> 00:27:25.310
[Sanchez] Three. four times a year.

494
00:27:25.393 --> 00:27:29.981
we got Bruce Weber photos
to put up in our store.

495
00:27:31.107 --> 00:27:35.236
When you're excited about
the unveil of the Bruce Weber photos…

496
00:27:35.320 --> 00:27:40.533
Who did they choose as the representative
of Abercrombie & Fitch?

497
00:27:41.660 --> 00:27:43.787
There's other brands for-- for everybody.

498
00:27:45.121 --> 00:27:46.748
That's Abercrombie & Fitch.

499
00:27:46.831 --> 00:27:50.627
It behooved me to get out
and recruit these types of people

500
00:27:51.127 --> 00:27:54.005
so that they could create an environment.

501
00:27:54.089 --> 00:27:55.757
How do you think you're gonna do?

502
00:27:56.341 --> 00:27:57.175
Pretty good.

503
00:27:57.759 --> 00:27:59.969
<i>♪ I'm head of the class ♪</i>

504
00:28:00.470 --> 00:28:02.263
<i>♪ I'm popular… ♪</i>

505
00:28:02.931 --> 00:28:06.726
[Denizet-Lewis] The stores would
each focus on a particular college campus.

506
00:28:06.810 --> 00:28:11.981
and they would try to recruit
the best-looking fraternity guys.

507
00:28:12.065 --> 00:28:14.359
If a fraternity guy was popular.

508
00:28:14.442 --> 00:28:16.986
other people would say.
"All right. what's he wearing?"

509
00:28:17.070 --> 00:28:18.363
And wanna copy that.

510
00:28:18.446 --> 00:28:20.407
♪ I'm <i>the party star ♪</i>

511
00:28:20.490 --> 00:28:22.283
<i>♪ I'm popular ♪</i>

512
00:28:22.367 --> 00:28:27.330
The bet was that if we get
the right guys on the right fraternities

513
00:28:27.414 --> 00:28:31.751
to wear the clothes and be ambassadors
for the clothes. then that's gonna--

514
00:28:31.835 --> 00:28:34.421
Other people are gonna wanna copy that.

515
00:28:34.504 --> 00:28:37.173
It was. like. pre-digital.
like. influencer marketing.

516
00:28:37.257 --> 00:28:38.758
As a manager at Abercrombie.

517
00:28:38.842 --> 00:28:42.011
they teach you very early on
about recruiting.

518
00:28:42.095 --> 00:28:44.389
You just-- You have to recruit.

519
00:28:44.472 --> 00:28:49.894
but not only do you have to recruit.
you have to recruit good-looking people.

520
00:28:49.978 --> 00:28:52.063
and this is what good-looking looks like.

521
00:28:52.147 --> 00:28:53.773
We literally had a book.

522
00:28:54.607 --> 00:28:56.192
[female voice] <i>Exhibiting the A&F look</i>

523
00:28:56.276 --> 00:28:59.988
<i>is a tremendously important part</i>
<i>of the overall experience</i>

524
00:29:00.071 --> 00:29:02.407
<i>at the Abercrombie & Fitch stores.</i>

525
00:29:02.490 --> 00:29:06.661
<i>Our people in the store</i>
<i>are an inspiration to the customer.</i>

526
00:29:06.745 --> 00:29:12.459
<i>A neatly combed. attractive.</i>
<i>natural. classic hairstyle is acceptable.</i>

527
00:29:13.084 --> 00:29:16.337
<i>Dreadlocks are unacceptable</i>
<i>for men and women.</i>

528
00:29:17.589 --> 00:29:19.924
<i>Gold chains are not acceptable for men.</i>

529
00:29:20.467 --> 00:29:24.763
<i>Women may wear</i>
<i>a thin. short. delicate silver necklace.</i>

530
00:29:24.846 --> 00:29:27.474
<i>Brand representatives are required to wear</i>

531
00:29:27.557 --> 00:29:30.018
<i>appropriate undergarments at all times.</i>

532
00:29:30.977 --> 00:29:32.020
<i>Natural.</i>

533
00:29:32.103 --> 00:29:33.313
<i>American.</i>

534
00:29:33.396 --> 00:29:34.606
<i>Classic.</i>

535
00:29:34.689 --> 00:29:36.399
<i>The A&F look.</i>

536
00:29:37.901 --> 00:29:43.281
No other mall brand went to the extreme
that Abercrombie did

537
00:29:43.364 --> 00:29:48.870
in micromanaging the look
of everything from the store

538
00:29:48.953 --> 00:29:52.624
down to. like. the person
who was cleaning up the stockroom.

539
00:29:52.707 --> 00:29:55.502
Jeffries was an extreme--

540
00:29:55.585 --> 00:29:58.254
He was very much a micromanager.

541
00:29:58.338 --> 00:30:03.384
I mean. if you look at the stores.
they were absolutely pristine. Right?

542
00:30:03.468 --> 00:30:06.638
I mean. it was--
Every detail. Mike cared about.

543
00:30:07.597 --> 00:30:10.725
[Rupp] Mike Jeffries was well-known
for his unannounced store visits.

544
00:30:10.809 --> 00:30:15.021
He cared about what stores looked like.
and he wanted to see them in person.

545
00:30:15.104 --> 00:30:17.106
A lot of people
have called them "blitzes."

546
00:30:17.190 --> 00:30:19.609
[Sanchez] So say a visit was on Friday.

547
00:30:19.692 --> 00:30:22.529
Monday. Tuesday. Wednesday. Thursday.

548
00:30:22.612 --> 00:30:24.614
you were doin' all-nights.

549
00:30:24.697 --> 00:30:28.034
This is where we gotta make sure.
like. everything is spick-and-span.

550
00:30:28.117 --> 00:30:29.536
Everything gets wiped down.

551
00:30:29.619 --> 00:30:30.954
There's no dust anywhere.

552
00:30:31.037 --> 00:30:33.164
The moose head looks clean.

553
00:30:33.665 --> 00:30:37.460
But the thing that mattered most. day-of.
was who was working.

554
00:30:37.544 --> 00:30:40.797
There were some people
that you kept on staff just for visits.

555
00:30:40.880 --> 00:30:45.677
It wasn't. "Hey. your store's not hitting
this number or hitting that number."

556
00:30:45.760 --> 00:30:48.346
It was. "You gotta get
more good-looking people in here."

557
00:30:48.847 --> 00:30:52.642
The high-water mark.
when we all finally knew that we made it.

558
00:30:52.725 --> 00:30:55.311
was when LFO came out with "Summer Girls."

559
00:30:55.395 --> 00:30:56.563
That LFO song.

560
00:30:56.646 --> 00:30:57.522
"Summer Girls."

561
00:30:57.605 --> 00:31:00.400
<i>♪ I like girls who wear</i>
<i>Abercrombie & Fitch ♪</i>

562
00:31:00.483 --> 00:31:02.360
"I like girls that wear
Abercrombie & Fitch."

563
00:31:02.443 --> 00:31:03.987
<i>♪ I'd take 'em if I had one wish ♪</i>

564
00:31:04.070 --> 00:31:06.739
"I think it's fly…"
Something about summer. "…the summer."

565
00:31:06.823 --> 00:31:09.576
It came out in the summer.
"We're doing something right."

566
00:31:10.618 --> 00:31:13.663
<i>♪ I like girls that wear</i>
<i>Abercrombie & Fitch ♪</i>

567
00:31:13.746 --> 00:31:15.582
<i>♪ I'd take her if I had one wish ♪</i>

568
00:31:16.165 --> 00:31:18.251
<i>♪ She's been gone since that summer… ♪</i>

569
00:31:18.334 --> 00:31:22.005
That was probably the coolest thing
that had ever happened to Mike Jeffries.

570
00:31:22.505 --> 00:31:25.466
In that moment. he'd knew he'd--
he'd done what he wanted.

571
00:31:26.634 --> 00:31:29.512
From a purely creative point of view.

572
00:31:30.054 --> 00:31:31.472
he was a mad genius.

573
00:31:31.556 --> 00:31:33.516
He knows what he's doing
and what he wants.

574
00:31:33.600 --> 00:31:36.686
and he's kinda like.
"I don't care what anyone else is doing."

575
00:31:36.769 --> 00:31:41.858
"I'm gonna do what I think
is beautiful. cool." you know. whatever.

576
00:31:41.941 --> 00:31:44.360
[sighs] And he did. He executed on it.

577
00:31:50.867 --> 00:31:55.413
So my first interaction with Abercrombie
was receiving a catalog out of the blue.

578
00:31:55.496 --> 00:31:57.415
I don't know how I got
on their mailing list.

579
00:31:57.498 --> 00:32:01.002
And I remember seeing
these young people smiling and frolicking.

580
00:32:01.085 --> 00:32:03.171
and I was like.
"When I'm in college. maybe…

581
00:32:03.671 --> 00:32:07.926
maybe I'm gonna hang out with my friends
in a field. like. arm-to-arm like this

582
00:32:08.009 --> 00:32:09.594
and jump around and. I don't know.

583
00:32:09.677 --> 00:32:12.347
get in a dog pile like they do
in these catalogs."

584
00:32:12.430 --> 00:32:13.723
[laughing] I don't know!

585
00:32:15.391 --> 00:32:17.769
My name's Phil Yu. I run a blog

586
00:32:17.852 --> 00:32:19.187
called <i>Angry Asian Man</i>

587
00:32:20.021 --> 00:32:23.775
to talk about my Asian American identity
and my community.

588
00:32:24.609 --> 00:32:28.237
I remember some readers
started sending photos to me about like.

589
00:32:28.321 --> 00:32:30.198
"Have you seen this shit at Abercrombie?"

590
00:32:30.281 --> 00:32:32.659
You know. and it was--
It was these T-shirts.

591
00:32:34.994 --> 00:32:39.332
Graphic tees for us were our personality.

592
00:32:40.792 --> 00:32:43.711
You know. we were moving at light speed.

593
00:32:43.795 --> 00:32:47.173
The graphic tee business
was a one and done type thing.

594
00:32:47.256 --> 00:32:50.802
so you had to continuously produce art.

595
00:32:51.511 --> 00:32:55.223
All those stupid slogans we put on there
and everything. that was us.

596
00:32:55.306 --> 00:32:56.599
We didn't have copywriters.

597
00:32:56.683 --> 00:32:59.018
They really wanted us to be irreverent.

598
00:32:59.102 --> 00:33:01.187
They really wanted us to be funny.

599
00:33:01.896 --> 00:33:06.109
relevant to that late teen.
early 20s. like. college crowd.

600
00:33:07.276 --> 00:33:09.487
[Sheahan] One of the themes
was Buddha Fest.

601
00:33:09.570 --> 00:33:13.324
and it had. like.
a cliché Asian big fat Buddha.

602
00:33:13.408 --> 00:33:15.952
I do remember one
that I got a kick out of that was like.

603
00:33:16.035 --> 00:33:19.122
"West Virginia.
no lifeguards in this gene pool."

604
00:33:19.205 --> 00:33:20.331
I laughed at the time.

605
00:33:20.415 --> 00:33:24.002
and now I'm like.
"That's really offensive and problematic."

606
00:33:24.085 --> 00:33:29.007
The second shirt on the table
was "Juan more for the road."

607
00:33:29.090 --> 00:33:32.468
So they had a donkey
holding a taco with a sombrero.

608
00:33:33.052 --> 00:33:34.679
The one that everybody remembers.

609
00:33:34.762 --> 00:33:38.933
Wong Brothers.
advertising a fictional laundry service.

610
00:33:39.017 --> 00:33:41.728
The slogan was.
"Two Wongs can make it white."

611
00:33:43.604 --> 00:33:45.398
Pop culture Orientalism. right?

612
00:33:45.481 --> 00:33:46.983
-[buzzer sounds]
-[grunts]

613
00:33:47.066 --> 00:33:50.653
[Yu] It's all this stuff taken from
people's understanding of Asians…

614
00:33:50.737 --> 00:33:51.612
[laughing]

615
00:33:51.696 --> 00:33:53.906
…if you just watched
American TV and movies.

616
00:33:53.990 --> 00:33:55.408
[gong sounds]

617
00:33:55.491 --> 00:33:58.244
What's happenin'. hot stuff?

618
00:33:58.327 --> 00:34:01.581
[Yu] So it's the kitschy font
and the-- sort of the caricatures

619
00:34:01.664 --> 00:34:04.542
of the buck-toothed
and the slant-eyed Asian. so…

620
00:34:05.043 --> 00:34:06.878
"Two Wongs can make it white."

621
00:34:08.921 --> 00:34:10.381
Asian Americans are often taught

622
00:34:10.465 --> 00:34:12.884
that you're supposed to
just keep your head down.

623
00:34:12.967 --> 00:34:14.177
not rock the boat.

624
00:34:14.677 --> 00:34:17.430
especially as a lot of us
are the children of immigrants.

625
00:34:17.513 --> 00:34:18.347
But I think

626
00:34:19.348 --> 00:34:22.351
at that moment. I was like.
"It's okay to be angry about this."

627
00:34:25.021 --> 00:34:28.107
[Gruys] I don't know what it was.
but. like. the kids.

628
00:34:28.191 --> 00:34:30.485
the consumers
just loved wearing those tees.

629
00:34:30.568 --> 00:34:31.944
so we kept makin' 'em.

630
00:34:32.904 --> 00:34:33.821
And they were cheap.

631
00:34:33.905 --> 00:34:37.158
You could sell tees
for. like. an 85% markup.

632
00:34:37.241 --> 00:34:38.993
Whenever something like this happens.

633
00:34:39.077 --> 00:34:41.996
I always imagined in my mind
a scenario where somebody. like--

634
00:34:42.080 --> 00:34:44.665
Man. if they just had
one person who was like.

635
00:34:44.749 --> 00:34:46.417
"Maybe this is not a good idea."

636
00:34:46.501 --> 00:34:48.753
I had nothing to do with whatever.
but I will say this.

637
00:34:48.836 --> 00:34:51.839
Two of the main team people
were Asian Americans.

638
00:34:52.340 --> 00:34:54.759
which is why
it got approved in the first place.

639
00:34:54.842 --> 00:34:58.930
You know. whenever-- This is--
I feel like you just dropped a bomb on me.

640
00:34:59.013 --> 00:35:02.016
In terms of-- What?
There was an Asian designer there?

641
00:35:02.100 --> 00:35:03.309
Maybe there was somebody.

642
00:35:03.392 --> 00:35:07.480
and then. you know. your cover is--
is the one Asian guy in the room.

643
00:35:07.563 --> 00:35:10.566
It's the one guy who's like. "I don't…"
"Do you find it offensive?"

644
00:35:10.650 --> 00:35:13.611
And is that guy really gonna be.
like. "No." I mean. "Yeah."

645
00:35:13.694 --> 00:35:16.656
Or is he gonna say-- Or is he gonna
flip over the table and be. like.

646
00:35:16.739 --> 00:35:19.200
"I-- No. I think this is
really offensive to my identity."

647
00:35:19.283 --> 00:35:23.037
In this corporate. stuffy environment
where everyone around you is white.

648
00:35:23.121 --> 00:35:24.080
and you're like--

649
00:35:24.163 --> 00:35:27.166
I don't know if that's really
a safe place to do that. right?

650
00:35:28.334 --> 00:35:30.044
[camera shutter clicking]

651
00:35:33.589 --> 00:35:35.633
This blatant racist product

652
00:35:35.716 --> 00:35:39.053
got a lot of Asian American students
particularly enraged.

653
00:35:39.554 --> 00:35:41.055
They were hitting them where.

654
00:35:41.139 --> 00:35:43.683
"This was supposed to be my jam.
supposed to be for me."

655
00:35:43.766 --> 00:35:47.019
and that's where the reaction
really started to grow amongst students.

656
00:35:47.103 --> 00:35:48.604
Asian American student groups.

657
00:35:48.688 --> 00:35:50.273
[crowd yelling]

658
00:35:53.985 --> 00:35:58.573
There's always people who don't really see
the pain behind something like that

659
00:35:58.656 --> 00:36:01.450
and just see it
as a funny thing that happened.

660
00:36:01.534 --> 00:36:03.911
The protest was nonviolent and orderly.

661
00:36:03.995 --> 00:36:06.205
but the same cannot be said
of the parking lot

662
00:36:06.289 --> 00:36:07.957
when they all went to drive home.

663
00:36:08.040 --> 00:36:09.667
[audience laughter]

664
00:36:10.668 --> 00:36:13.212
[producer] Let's talk about
the Two Wongs shirt.

665
00:36:13.296 --> 00:36:16.299
That shirt-- That's one of the tees
that I remember. [laughs]

666
00:36:16.382 --> 00:36:19.468
Mike would pull everything
back from the stores.

667
00:36:19.552 --> 00:36:21.345
and we actually would burn them

668
00:36:22.680 --> 00:36:26.851
to make sure nobody ever ended up
getting the merchandise.

669
00:36:28.102 --> 00:36:30.021
But they kept
the "Juan more for the road."

670
00:36:30.104 --> 00:36:32.565
Clearly. it was. like. a donkey. you know.

671
00:36:33.065 --> 00:36:35.318
Obviously.
they were insinuating something.

672
00:36:37.486 --> 00:36:39.363
[Yu] The poor publicist
who has to write this.

673
00:36:39.447 --> 00:36:44.619
they actually said. "We thought
that Asians would love these shirts."

674
00:36:44.702 --> 00:36:47.496
That's from a press release
from-- from Abercrombie.

675
00:36:47.580 --> 00:36:51.500
We were always just trying to be
quick-witted and things like that.

676
00:36:51.584 --> 00:36:54.879
And. um… I know
that we made a couple mistakes.

677
00:36:54.962 --> 00:36:58.716
We kind of owned up to our responsibility.

678
00:36:58.799 --> 00:36:59.800
made it

679
00:37:00.927 --> 00:37:03.346
right as fast as we could.

680
00:37:03.429 --> 00:37:07.016
and then we kind of.
you know. learned and moved on.

681
00:37:07.892 --> 00:37:11.062
Then we would get in trouble.
and. "Don't do that again."

682
00:37:11.145 --> 00:37:13.439
"But do something just like it." you know.

683
00:37:14.106 --> 00:37:17.526
Obviously. it's from the top down
if they approve those kinds of shirts.

684
00:37:17.610 --> 00:37:21.239
of what there… what might have been
going on behind the scenes.

685
00:37:23.115 --> 00:37:25.451
You know.
they're operating in a bubble. right?

686
00:37:25.534 --> 00:37:29.664
They're operating in a place
where they don't see what it comes down to

687
00:37:29.747 --> 00:37:33.209
at that consumer level
of this Asian kid looking at these shirts

688
00:37:33.292 --> 00:37:35.127
and being like. "What is this bullshit?"

689
00:37:35.211 --> 00:37:37.463
Or being confused.
"Is this supposed to be cool?"

690
00:37:37.546 --> 00:37:41.342
Like. "This is all I see of myself
when I look at pop culture."

691
00:37:41.425 --> 00:37:44.804
Like. "Maybe this is
what I'm supposed to accept

692
00:37:44.887 --> 00:37:46.722
as an Asian American." you know.

693
00:37:47.723 --> 00:37:53.980
The first time I became aware
of the image becoming problematic for me

694
00:37:54.063 --> 00:37:56.440
was Sam Raimi's <i>Spider-Man.</i>

695
00:37:56.524 --> 00:37:58.901
I think it came out in 2001.
with Tobey Maguire.

696
00:37:58.985 --> 00:38:00.319
Flash. it was just an accident!

697
00:38:00.403 --> 00:38:04.073
If you know the comics. Peter Parker's
biggest bully is Flash Thompson.

698
00:38:04.156 --> 00:38:08.286
and he's traditionally been
a big. blond. like. asshole.

699
00:38:08.369 --> 00:38:11.622
In the movie. he is dressed head-to-toe
in Abercrombie the entire time.

700
00:38:11.706 --> 00:38:13.916
and it really upset me.
It really. really upset me.

701
00:38:14.000 --> 00:38:17.545
I was like. "That's not good."
I knew it wasn't good. Know what I mean?

702
00:38:17.628 --> 00:38:20.047
'Cause something had shifted there. so…

703
00:38:20.131 --> 00:38:22.550
[producer] Before that.
what did Abercrombie signify to you?

704
00:38:22.633 --> 00:38:25.761
It was-- It was a cool kid
who would never do anything like that.

705
00:38:26.262 --> 00:38:28.889
<i>♪ I'm the head of the class ♪</i>

706
00:38:28.973 --> 00:38:31.100
<i>♪ I'm popular</i> ♪

707
00:38:31.183 --> 00:38:35.521
In 2003. I was a retail reporter
at <i>The Wall Street Journal.</i>

708
00:38:35.604 --> 00:38:40.109
and. um. I'm in New York. visiting stores.

709
00:38:40.609 --> 00:38:44.071
A colleague and I walk into
this American Eagle Outfitters store.

710
00:38:44.155 --> 00:38:47.033
My colleague immediately starts
chatting up the manager.

711
00:38:47.116 --> 00:38:50.119
She asked. "How'd you end up
at American Eagle Outfitters?"

712
00:38:50.202 --> 00:38:53.706
And she says. "I was a district manager
for Abercrombie & Fitch.

713
00:38:53.789 --> 00:38:56.208
and then I moved over."
And my colleague says.

714
00:38:56.292 --> 00:38:57.710
"Oh. that's interesting."

715
00:38:57.793 --> 00:39:02.298
"It's a slightly different culture.
trying to keep everybody brand positive."

716
00:39:02.381 --> 00:39:07.219
And this manager just starts crying.

717
00:39:07.303 --> 00:39:10.014
And she's like. "I'm so happy here."

718
00:39:10.097 --> 00:39:12.391
"I get to hire who I want."

719
00:39:12.475 --> 00:39:16.020
She gestures to the guy
who's leading women to the dressing room.

720
00:39:16.103 --> 00:39:18.731
who's. like. a light-skinned Black guy
with dreadlocks.

721
00:39:19.231 --> 00:39:23.694
And my colleague sort of nods
like she understands what is being said.

722
00:39:24.195 --> 00:39:26.197
I'm clearly not getting something here.

723
00:39:27.323 --> 00:39:32.453
So I started interviewing people who had
Abercrombie & Fitch on their résumés.

724
00:39:32.536 --> 00:39:34.455
and. essentially. what I learned was.

725
00:39:34.538 --> 00:39:38.709
most people were recruited
for the job on the basis of their looks.

726
00:39:40.586 --> 00:39:44.715
What I started to sense
was that they were firing people too.

727
00:39:44.799 --> 00:39:47.510
And that was the thing that really got me.

728
00:39:47.593 --> 00:39:50.554
because that seemed
like it maybe wasn't legal?

729
00:39:50.638 --> 00:39:57.061
So I finally found a manager.
um. to sort of tell me. "Listen.

730
00:39:57.645 --> 00:40:02.942
you have to rank all your employees
on the scale of. like. cool to rocks."

731
00:40:03.025 --> 00:40:04.360
"And if they aren't at least cool.

732
00:40:04.443 --> 00:40:07.238
then you have to zero them out
off the schedule."

733
00:40:07.321 --> 00:40:09.073
It didn't matter what your sales were.

734
00:40:09.156 --> 00:40:14.203
All that mattered was that
the employees that you took pictures of

735
00:40:14.286 --> 00:40:17.331
and sent back to headquarters were hot.

736
00:40:18.666 --> 00:40:20.292
Clearly this is illegal?

737
00:40:21.001 --> 00:40:21.919
Right?

738
00:40:23.838 --> 00:40:26.549
I wasn't ever scheduled a ton of hours.

739
00:40:26.632 --> 00:40:28.384
So I went to one of the managers.

740
00:40:28.467 --> 00:40:30.803
and I said.
"Hey. can I have more day shifts?"

741
00:40:30.886 --> 00:40:33.889
And he said. "You know.
there aren't any. They're packed."

742
00:40:33.973 --> 00:40:35.683
"All we have are these night shifts."

743
00:40:35.766 --> 00:40:40.187
I remember telling him.
"I don't like vacuuming." you know.

744
00:40:40.271 --> 00:40:42.022
"I don't like cleaning the windows."

745
00:40:42.106 --> 00:40:46.068
and he told me. "But. Carla.
you're such a good window washer."

746
00:40:46.152 --> 00:40:47.695
"You're so good at it."

747
00:40:47.778 --> 00:40:50.531
And I told him.
"Well. you know. I can swap with someone."

748
00:40:50.614 --> 00:40:53.409
"My friend said she'd be fine
to swap this four-hour shift."

749
00:40:53.492 --> 00:40:55.411
"She doesn't mind working at night."

750
00:40:55.494 --> 00:40:57.663
"Well. no.
we don't like you guys to swap."

751
00:40:57.746 --> 00:41:00.124
"If you were assigned that shift.
you were assigned it."

752
00:41:00.207 --> 00:41:03.502
So I complain to my girlfriend.
"I can't believe this. What is going on?"

753
00:41:03.586 --> 00:41:06.255
She told me. "I bet they're not
scheduling you because you're Black."

754
00:41:06.338 --> 00:41:08.215
"Like. no other Black people work there."

755
00:41:09.216 --> 00:41:11.302
When she said that.
it was one of those. like…

756
00:41:11.385 --> 00:41:14.346
"Oh. I know.
Like. in the heart of my heart. I know."

757
00:41:14.430 --> 00:41:15.473
"I know that's why.

758
00:41:15.556 --> 00:41:17.600
but maybe I can do something
to overcome that."

759
00:41:17.683 --> 00:41:20.978
"This is a company.
This isn't. like. one person

760
00:41:21.979 --> 00:41:22.813
stopping me."

761
00:41:22.897 --> 00:41:25.858
And then after that.
I was not on the schedule.

762
00:41:25.941 --> 00:41:29.570
And I remember asking him.
"What should I do? Do I still work here?"

763
00:41:29.653 --> 00:41:32.156
"I haven't been on the schedule
in two months."

764
00:41:32.239 --> 00:41:34.742
and he's like.
"No. you do. Just keep calling us."

765
00:41:35.367 --> 00:41:37.953
I knew I had been fired.
and I just moved on.

766
00:41:38.037 --> 00:41:39.663
I mean. there wasn't a resignation.

767
00:41:39.747 --> 00:41:43.501
There wasn't anyone that called me.
I just… It was over.

768
00:41:45.377 --> 00:41:48.380
Where our store was
was in very close proximity to UC Irvine.

769
00:41:48.464 --> 00:41:52.301
UC Irvine is known as UCI.
University of Chinese and Indians.

770
00:41:52.384 --> 00:41:53.802
It's. like. 75% Asian.

771
00:41:53.886 --> 00:41:56.722
Korean. Indian. Chinese. Japanese.

772
00:41:56.805 --> 00:41:58.849
So it wasn't a surprise

773
00:41:58.933 --> 00:42:02.853
that a lot of the staff
were of Asian descent.

774
00:42:03.521 --> 00:42:09.693
We finished the holiday season.
and we're notified by a note saying.

775
00:42:09.777 --> 00:42:14.323
"If you don't have a paycheck." you know.
"you've been let go for the season."

776
00:42:14.406 --> 00:42:16.784
My name wasn't on the list.

777
00:42:16.867 --> 00:42:21.539
so I talked to my other friends.

778
00:42:21.622 --> 00:42:25.000
I was like. "My name wasn't on the list.
Did you guys--"

779
00:42:25.084 --> 00:42:26.835
They're like. "We're not on the list."

780
00:42:26.919 --> 00:42:28.712
And I was like. "That's super weird."

781
00:42:28.796 --> 00:42:32.007
Then we talked to our assistant manager.
who's Asian American.

782
00:42:32.091 --> 00:42:35.719
He said the real reason
is because after the corporate blitz.

783
00:42:35.803 --> 00:42:38.931
one of the people from corporate
went around.

784
00:42:39.014 --> 00:42:42.309
and they noticed
a bunch of Asian people in the store.

785
00:42:42.393 --> 00:42:45.062
They said. "You need more staff
that looks like this."

786
00:42:45.145 --> 00:42:47.773
And they pointed to an Abercrombie poster.

787
00:42:47.856 --> 00:42:50.359
and it was-- it was a Caucasian model.

788
00:42:54.363 --> 00:42:57.992
It hurt because I had such
a positive experience with this company.

789
00:42:58.075 --> 00:42:59.577
and to find out they were like.

790
00:42:59.660 --> 00:43:01.996
"No. we don't want you
because of the way you look."

791
00:43:02.079 --> 00:43:03.497
it actually was very hurtful.

792
00:43:04.456 --> 00:43:06.208
Then I took all the posters down.

793
00:43:06.292 --> 00:43:09.920
It was because I didn't look like
those people in the photograph

794
00:43:10.004 --> 00:43:12.256
that that's why
I didn't work there anymore.

795
00:43:12.756 --> 00:43:13.841
I was mad.

796
00:43:13.924 --> 00:43:18.721
But what are you gonna do?
We're. like. 21-year-olds. What do you do?

797
00:43:18.804 --> 00:43:21.557
It seemed super explicit.

798
00:43:21.640 --> 00:43:24.518
I went to the store.

799
00:43:24.602 --> 00:43:26.812
I spoke with whoever was working there.

800
00:43:26.895 --> 00:43:28.981
and she said.
"I'm sorry. We can't rehire you."

801
00:43:29.064 --> 00:43:30.816
And I asked. "Why not?"

802
00:43:31.567 --> 00:43:34.570
And she said.
"My manager said we can't rehire you

803
00:43:34.653 --> 00:43:38.073
'cause we already have
too many Filipinos working at this store."

804
00:43:39.783 --> 00:43:41.744
I was like. "Are you serious?"

805
00:43:41.827 --> 00:43:45.623
And she looked pretty uncomfortable.
and she was like. "Yeah."

806
00:43:46.624 --> 00:43:48.709
At no point did I ever say I was Filipino.

807
00:43:48.792 --> 00:43:51.629
so that was a guess on the part
of the person that worked there

808
00:43:51.712 --> 00:43:52.921
that I was Filipino.

809
00:43:53.631 --> 00:43:57.051
I remember telling my parents.
and I told close friends.

810
00:43:57.134 --> 00:44:01.513
They heard it and they very much agreed
with me that that was fucked up.

811
00:44:01.597 --> 00:44:04.391
I guess people didn't know what to do.
including my parents.

812
00:44:04.475 --> 00:44:06.393
Like. what do you tell your kid

813
00:44:06.477 --> 00:44:11.106
when someone says that we can't hire you
'cause of who you are?

814
00:44:11.190 --> 00:44:13.567
I talked to my mom
about everything going on.

815
00:44:13.651 --> 00:44:16.528
and she basically said.

816
00:44:16.612 --> 00:44:19.782
"I'm really surprised
that you even wanted to work there."

817
00:44:19.865 --> 00:44:22.117
She's like.
"I'm sure you were fine to clean up.

818
00:44:22.701 --> 00:44:26.121
but that store made it clear.
from my eyes.

819
00:44:26.205 --> 00:44:28.415
that they didn't want
people like us there."

820
00:44:28.499 --> 00:44:31.168
She's like.
"I honestly didn't expect anything else."

821
00:44:31.251 --> 00:44:35.839
"That store. everything about that store
screamed that we were an other."

822
00:44:35.923 --> 00:44:36.924
"We didn't fit there."

823
00:44:37.841 --> 00:44:39.593
[male voice]
<i>Walk into any upscale boutique.</i>

824
00:44:39.677 --> 00:44:43.764
<i>and you'll see salespeople who look like</i>
<i>they walked off the fashion pages.</i>

825
00:44:43.847 --> 00:44:47.476
<i>Retailers seek out workers</i>
<i>whose look they feel will sell clothes.</i>

826
00:44:47.559 --> 00:44:51.271
<i>But can maintaining that look</i>
<i>become a form of racial discrimination?</i>

827
00:44:51.355 --> 00:44:53.774
<i>That's what the firm</i>
<i>of Abercrombie & Fitch</i>

828
00:44:53.857 --> 00:44:55.025
<i>is being accused of.</i>

829
00:44:55.109 --> 00:44:58.904
The nine plaintiffs in this new suit
claim they were fired or not hired

830
00:44:58.987 --> 00:45:00.906
because they weren't white enough.

831
00:45:00.989 --> 00:45:02.950
When I did get scheduled.

832
00:45:03.033 --> 00:45:05.828
I would have to come in at closing time.

833
00:45:05.911 --> 00:45:11.083
I was one of the named plaintiffs
on the Abercrombie lawsuit.

834
00:45:11.166 --> 00:45:13.585
Joining me now
are two of the plaintiffs in this suit.

835
00:45:13.669 --> 00:45:15.963
Anthony Ocampo and Jennifer Lu.

836
00:45:16.046 --> 00:45:19.299
I am one of the people
that sued Abercrombie. [laughs]

837
00:45:19.383 --> 00:45:23.137
[Sheahan] We wanted to represent
the people that this had happened to

838
00:45:23.220 --> 00:45:27.891
and give them a voice and make sure
that Abercrombie was held accountable.

839
00:45:27.975 --> 00:45:29.727
All-American doesn't mean all-white.

840
00:45:29.810 --> 00:45:32.771
One of my friends. who's Mexican-American.
was working for MALDEF.

841
00:45:32.855 --> 00:45:35.441
the Mexican American Legal Defense
and Education Fund.

842
00:45:35.524 --> 00:45:37.651
and he was working for Tom Saenz.

843
00:45:37.735 --> 00:45:41.447
and it turns out
that Tom had heard other rumblings

844
00:45:41.530 --> 00:45:44.199
of people being discriminated
at Abercrombie.

845
00:45:46.076 --> 00:45:48.412
[Saenz]
In this case. I could go to the mall

846
00:45:48.495 --> 00:45:52.708
and verify what our client had told us.
and so I did that.

847
00:45:52.791 --> 00:45:55.210
I would go into the A&F store.

848
00:45:55.294 --> 00:45:58.422
and I would look at
who the retail workers were.

849
00:45:58.505 --> 00:46:00.716
And then I'd literally cross the hall

850
00:46:00.799 --> 00:46:03.218
and go to a similar retail establishment.

851
00:46:03.302 --> 00:46:05.179
whether it was Old Navy

852
00:46:05.262 --> 00:46:09.266
or Banana Republic or the Gap.

853
00:46:09.349 --> 00:46:11.602
and the contrast was just striking.

854
00:46:11.685 --> 00:46:13.103
In those other stores.

855
00:46:13.187 --> 00:46:16.774
you would see a workforce
that looked like Southern California.

856
00:46:16.857 --> 00:46:20.861
mostly young people of color
doing the retail work.

857
00:46:20.944 --> 00:46:22.196
At Abercrombie & Fitch.

858
00:46:22.279 --> 00:46:26.241
it was almost entirely
white retail workers.

859
00:46:26.325 --> 00:46:29.244
We're not talking about
a single individual who was denied a job.

860
00:46:29.328 --> 00:46:32.372
as terrible as that is
and as unlawful as that is.

861
00:46:32.456 --> 00:46:35.876
We're talking about practices
going on across the country

862
00:46:35.959 --> 00:46:39.713
at hundreds of stores
affecting thousands of students.

863
00:46:41.006 --> 00:46:45.719
It was actually difficult
to find folks who could be plaintiffs.

864
00:46:45.803 --> 00:46:48.806
and that's in part
because there were so few people of color

865
00:46:48.889 --> 00:46:51.350
who were employed by Abercrombie & Fitch.

866
00:46:51.433 --> 00:46:54.895
My younger sister text me. or called me.

867
00:46:54.978 --> 00:46:58.482
I don't think we were texting then.
I think it was way too expensive!

868
00:46:58.565 --> 00:46:59.983
But she called me and said.

869
00:47:00.067 --> 00:47:03.278
"I saw this thing on the Internet
about Abercrombie & Fitch

870
00:47:03.362 --> 00:47:05.531
in a racial discrimination lawsuit."

871
00:47:05.614 --> 00:47:09.284
and she's like. "They definitely
racially discriminated against you!"

872
00:47:09.368 --> 00:47:11.370
[laughs] Um. "You should call them."

873
00:47:11.453 --> 00:47:16.750
I was like. "I wonder
if what happened to me was 'bad enough'."

874
00:47:16.834 --> 00:47:18.919
You know? If that's some-- Does it even--

875
00:47:19.002 --> 00:47:21.588
If I tell them.
would they just be like. "Just move on"?

876
00:47:21.672 --> 00:47:23.632
There was still that piece of.

877
00:47:23.715 --> 00:47:25.425
"It wasn't that bad."

878
00:47:25.509 --> 00:47:28.679
um. where if you look at things
like racism

879
00:47:28.762 --> 00:47:31.223
or sexism or homophobia that…

880
00:47:31.849 --> 00:47:35.060
It does-- Things don't have to
look "that<i> </i>bad."

881
00:47:35.143 --> 00:47:37.062
Someone doesn't have to call you--

882
00:47:37.145 --> 00:47:40.858
Someone doesn't have to call me a nigger
in the middle of Abercrombie & Fitch

883
00:47:40.941 --> 00:47:43.610
for it to be "bad enough."

884
00:47:43.694 --> 00:47:48.615
Um. but. you know. 19-year-old Carla.
I'm thinking. "Well. I don't know."

885
00:47:48.699 --> 00:47:51.034
I've never seen racism that explicit.

886
00:47:51.118 --> 00:47:52.661
I was really pissed off.

887
00:47:52.744 --> 00:47:55.038
Like. I was enraged.
and it never went away.

888
00:47:55.122 --> 00:47:57.875
And so when I was invited
to be part of the lawsuit.

889
00:47:57.958 --> 00:47:59.042
I thought. "Oh. okay."

890
00:47:59.126 --> 00:48:04.131
"Here's an opportunity to…
to call Abercrombie on their bullshit

891
00:48:04.214 --> 00:48:06.800
of trying to say
they're an all-American brand.

892
00:48:06.884 --> 00:48:09.970
and yet the way they're maintaining
this image of all-American

893
00:48:10.053 --> 00:48:13.891
is to hire a bunch of white folks
and fire a bunch of people of color."

894
00:48:13.974 --> 00:48:17.644
[man 13] We just asked them. what was
their experience working for Abercrombie.

895
00:48:17.728 --> 00:48:20.022
attempting to apply
to work at Abercrombie.

896
00:48:20.105 --> 00:48:25.736
and themes started to emerge of this
strong. strong preference for white people

897
00:48:25.819 --> 00:48:28.989
over African Americans.
Latinos. Asian Americans.

898
00:48:29.072 --> 00:48:31.742
anybody who didn't fit
this particular look.

899
00:48:31.825 --> 00:48:36.371
I was sick of getting my schedule back
every week with lines through names.

900
00:48:36.455 --> 00:48:37.998
Essentially telling people

901
00:48:38.081 --> 00:48:39.958
they don't look good enough.

902
00:48:40.042 --> 00:48:43.837
I can't look the people that work for me
that wanna be there in the eye and say.

903
00:48:43.921 --> 00:48:47.215
you know. lie to them
and say. "Oh. we don't have hours."

904
00:48:48.550 --> 00:48:50.719
When it's because
they weren't pretty enough.

905
00:48:51.470 --> 00:48:55.098
[Barrientos] Jahan talked to us
about what Abercrombie was saying.

906
00:48:55.182 --> 00:48:58.101
It wasn't that we were being
racially discriminated against.

907
00:48:58.185 --> 00:49:01.480
It was that we weren't good-looking enough
to work on the floor.

908
00:49:01.563 --> 00:49:03.899
We're just-- just ugly! [laughs]

909
00:49:03.982 --> 00:49:05.859
It was seriously laughable. We…

910
00:49:06.401 --> 00:49:09.363
When we got together. we were like.
"Are you kidding me? What a joke."

911
00:49:09.446 --> 00:49:12.449
I guess it's better that than saying.

912
00:49:12.532 --> 00:49:14.910
"We racially discriminate
against these people."

913
00:49:15.577 --> 00:49:18.622
[laughs] But it was a joke.
It was seriously a joke.

914
00:49:23.877 --> 00:49:27.255
[Sanchez] Abercrombie got sued
in a class-action lawsuit

915
00:49:27.339 --> 00:49:29.758
for putting brown and Black people
in the back.

916
00:49:36.014 --> 00:49:37.557
Whoo!

917
00:49:37.641 --> 00:49:42.104
Abercrombie & Fitch denied the allegations
but settled-- but settled the suit.

918
00:49:42.187 --> 00:49:45.941
Abercrombie really knew
that they had a lot to hide

919
00:49:46.024 --> 00:49:48.360
and offered them
a big settlement right away.

920
00:49:48.860 --> 00:49:53.865
[Berfield] Abercrombie & Fitch
was required to pay almost $50 million

921
00:49:55.784 --> 00:49:57.160
and to make some changes.

922
00:49:59.579 --> 00:50:02.541
Abercrombie agreed
to enter into a consent decree.

923
00:50:19.933 --> 00:50:25.731
[Berfield] So Abercrombie had to create
the position of Chief Diversity Officer.

924
00:50:27.315 --> 00:50:28.859
On one hand. like. great opportunity

925
00:50:28.942 --> 00:50:32.571
to take a company. you know.
that really needs you.

926
00:50:32.654 --> 00:50:34.156
[laughs]

927
00:50:34.239 --> 00:50:36.408
"Do they want you?" is the other question.

928
00:50:39.703 --> 00:50:43.540
I got a call from a search firm.
"Listen. there's an opportunity in Ohio."

929
00:50:43.623 --> 00:50:46.460
"It's a brand called A&F."
I said. "I don't know what that is."

930
00:50:46.543 --> 00:50:48.754
So I went to the mall
and tried to figure it out.

931
00:50:48.837 --> 00:50:52.424
I walked around. I shopped and I looked.
and I said. "Oh. It's different."

932
00:50:55.802 --> 00:50:57.554
I began to figure out what it was about.

933
00:50:57.637 --> 00:50:59.765
which was figuring out
how to reinvent a brand

934
00:50:59.848 --> 00:51:04.269
from the perspective of D&I.
which at the time was not a function.

935
00:51:04.352 --> 00:51:07.064
There was not an office. not a discipline.
There was no muscle.

936
00:51:07.147 --> 00:51:08.982
I had to figure out
how to put it all together.

937
00:51:09.066 --> 00:51:11.234
I said.
"Well. you've been praying to God."

938
00:51:11.318 --> 00:51:12.986
"You've been saying
you need something big."

939
00:51:13.070 --> 00:51:15.864
"I guess he's telling you right now.
this is probably it."

940
00:51:17.866 --> 00:51:20.619
So I asked about
the reporting relationship.

941
00:51:20.702 --> 00:51:22.913
which was the biggest thing
for me to figure out.

942
00:51:22.996 --> 00:51:25.707
and I knew that it would be
to the CEO and chairman.

943
00:51:28.293 --> 00:51:30.337
The work there had inherent challenges.

944
00:51:30.420 --> 00:51:33.090
I had to figure out
how to navigate a lot of them.

945
00:51:33.173 --> 00:51:35.008
Some of the challenges were around.

946
00:51:35.092 --> 00:51:40.055
"How do you create a brand
with fewer contradictions?"

947
00:51:49.189 --> 00:51:52.192
We approach people every day
with our inclusive mindset

948
00:51:52.275 --> 00:51:53.860
that embraces our diversity.

949
00:51:53.944 --> 00:51:56.404
-Come work with me in New York.
-Arizona.

950
00:51:56.488 --> 00:51:57.531
-Florida.
-Belgium.

951
00:51:57.614 --> 00:51:58.824
-Spain.
-Hong Kong.

952
00:51:58.907 --> 00:52:00.158
-Germany.
-[in unison] The UK.

953
00:52:04.079 --> 00:52:07.666
Someone like myself going into
those circumstances and situations.

954
00:52:07.749 --> 00:52:08.834
you understand. like.

955
00:52:09.835 --> 00:52:12.629
maybe this is a form of "tokenism."

956
00:52:13.213 --> 00:52:19.261
Now. you could either say.
"No way am I going to be a part of that."

957
00:52:19.344 --> 00:52:23.598
or you can look at it as an opportunity

958
00:52:23.682 --> 00:52:26.977
and then open that door even wider
for people like yourself

959
00:52:27.060 --> 00:52:31.815
and others who haven't necessarily had
that sort of access or opportunity.

960
00:52:32.482 --> 00:52:35.485
[Sanchez] I was a recruiter for a couple
years. developing relationships

961
00:52:35.569 --> 00:52:38.613
on historically Black colleges
and universities.

962
00:52:39.114 --> 00:52:42.617
As a brown man
who very much appears to be white.

963
00:52:42.701 --> 00:52:44.411
wearing all Abercrombie & Fitch.

964
00:52:44.494 --> 00:52:48.373
'cause that's what
we're required to do on campus. you're--

965
00:52:48.456 --> 00:52:52.377
At first. you're getting some dirty looks.
and rightfully so.

966
00:52:52.460 --> 00:52:53.795
When I walked in.

967
00:52:54.963 --> 00:52:57.340
I think 90% of their population was white.

968
00:52:57.924 --> 00:52:59.384
By year five or six.

969
00:52:59.467 --> 00:53:03.221
population went above 53% non-white.

970
00:53:05.891 --> 00:53:10.187
When I transitioned over
to my role in Diversity & Inclusion.

971
00:53:10.770 --> 00:53:16.109
my first meeting
where I was with the store's leadership.

972
00:53:16.193 --> 00:53:19.654
and they were talking about
what we wanted in the stores.

973
00:53:20.238 --> 00:53:25.076
the free. sort of. free flow
of how we talked about beauty

974
00:53:25.160 --> 00:53:27.454
and who was good-looking.
who was not good-looking.

975
00:53:27.537 --> 00:53:29.331
or that person's nose was this or that.

976
00:53:29.414 --> 00:53:32.417
I was like. "I can't believe
we literally talk about people

977
00:53:32.500 --> 00:53:35.212
and dissect people's features like this."

978
00:53:35.295 --> 00:53:39.341
Or. like. it would be written
in a. you know. like. the interview.

979
00:53:39.424 --> 00:53:41.009
like. "Nope." like…

980
00:53:41.092 --> 00:53:44.387
It was just-- I couldn't believe it.
to be honest with you. I was shocked.

981
00:53:44.971 --> 00:53:47.057
[Tkacik] Brand reps
were no longer called "brand reps."

982
00:53:47.140 --> 00:53:50.810
They were called either "impact."
and that meant that you went to the back.

983
00:53:50.894 --> 00:53:54.314
or "model."
and that meant you could be up front.

984
00:53:54.397 --> 00:53:56.483
I think that. like. the idea was that

985
00:53:56.566 --> 00:54:00.654
calling their minimum wage
retail employees "models."

986
00:54:00.737 --> 00:54:03.949
you know. Abercrombie could
get away with anything

987
00:54:04.032 --> 00:54:06.243
that a modeling agency
could get away with.

988
00:54:06.326 --> 00:54:10.830
They never put it in words that they were
to be good-looking post-consent decree.

989
00:54:10.914 --> 00:54:15.418
and I think they were more careful
about not necessarily using that word.

990
00:54:15.502 --> 00:54:17.045
but they took care of it

991
00:54:17.128 --> 00:54:20.882
when they got it approved with
the consent decree to call them models.

992
00:54:21.383 --> 00:54:25.220
You took care of it.
Like. nothin' changed as far as that went.

993
00:54:25.303 --> 00:54:28.014
[producer] So. what if an ugly person
applied to be a model?

994
00:54:28.098 --> 00:54:28.974
They interviewed.

995
00:54:30.141 --> 00:54:33.520
They went through the same interview
process that the other folks went through.

996
00:54:34.020 --> 00:54:36.231
[producer] But does that mean
they had just as little shot

997
00:54:36.314 --> 00:54:38.316
pre- and post-consent decree
of getting a job?

998
00:54:38.400 --> 00:54:39.234
Oh yeah.

999
00:54:39.943 --> 00:54:40.777
Yeah.

1000
00:54:42.404 --> 00:54:46.199
[Tkacik] The consent decree did not force
leadership to change at all.

1001
00:54:46.283 --> 00:54:49.703
The entire leadership structure
remained in place.

1002
00:54:49.786 --> 00:54:53.581
At that point. Jeffries still had
almost 10% of the stock.

1003
00:54:53.665 --> 00:54:56.876
Um. so nothing. nothing changed at all.

1004
00:54:58.378 --> 00:55:01.006
A lot of these things
come from the top down.

1005
00:55:02.048 --> 00:55:04.718
Between Jeffries and Bruce Weber.

1006
00:55:04.801 --> 00:55:08.346
we have some really troubling behavior.

1007
00:55:15.979 --> 00:55:18.481
Bruce Weber was able
to take advantage of his power more

1008
00:55:18.565 --> 00:55:20.817
because he was so infamous
and so out there.

1009
00:55:20.900 --> 00:55:22.736
It was very well known with Bruce

1010
00:55:22.819 --> 00:55:24.779
that he… liked…

1011
00:55:26.072 --> 00:55:26.990
young men.

1012
00:55:27.490 --> 00:55:30.785
He's gonna invite you over
and try his "good touch. bad touch" thing.

1013
00:55:30.869 --> 00:55:31.786
You would

1014
00:55:32.871 --> 00:55:34.164
put your hand on your chest.

1015
00:55:35.040 --> 00:55:39.294
and he'd put his hand on your hand.
kind of like talking to relax.

1016
00:55:39.377 --> 00:55:42.922
And then it was.
"I'm gonna lower your hand."

1017
00:55:43.006 --> 00:55:45.300
"Tell me when to stop."

1018
00:55:45.383 --> 00:55:47.218
My hand didn't move. [laughs]

1019
00:55:47.302 --> 00:55:48.511
So he's like-- he's like.

1020
00:55:48.595 --> 00:55:51.014
"No. we're gonna lower your hand.
and then when I--"

1021
00:55:51.097 --> 00:55:53.975
And I'm like. "No. that's…
We're just… We're good."

1022
00:55:54.059 --> 00:55:57.562
There was a guy
that would get a call from Bruce.

1023
00:55:57.645 --> 00:55:59.898
He would get invited
to come over for dinner.

1024
00:56:00.648 --> 00:56:03.360
Like. "Hey. you should come over.
I'm gonna have dinner."

1025
00:56:03.443 --> 00:56:05.195
"Play with my dogs." Blah. blah. blah.

1026
00:56:05.278 --> 00:56:08.031
Then they'd go over.
and I would not see them the next day.

1027
00:56:08.531 --> 00:56:11.284
It was day three. and all of a sudden.
like. the phone rings.

1028
00:56:11.368 --> 00:56:14.913
and I'm like. "Oh. I know what that is."

1029
00:56:14.996 --> 00:56:20.043
"Hey. Bobby. So I'm sending you a car
to come over for dinner."

1030
00:56:20.126 --> 00:56:24.672
And at this moment. the moment is like.
I'm gonna go home or not.

1031
00:56:24.756 --> 00:56:27.008
"Yeah. so I'm not gonna be able
to make it."

1032
00:56:27.092 --> 00:56:30.053
And he's like. "What? No. you have
to come. It's great for your career."

1033
00:56:30.136 --> 00:56:33.515
So I'm like. "No. I'm cool. Bruce.
but thank you very much."

1034
00:56:33.598 --> 00:56:36.434
And all of a sudden.
my phone rings in probably one minute.

1035
00:56:36.518 --> 00:56:39.979
Let's say less than two minutes.
it rang again. I was like. "What?"

1036
00:56:40.063 --> 00:56:42.190
And I pick it up.
and he's like. "Hey. Bobby."

1037
00:56:42.273 --> 00:56:45.568
"Unfortunately. you're gonna be cut.
and your flight's ready."

1038
00:56:45.652 --> 00:56:49.739
"And your bags… Get your bags ready.
And then you have a flight tonight."

1039
00:56:49.823 --> 00:56:52.575
It was just like.
in that instant. I was done.

1040
00:56:54.786 --> 00:56:56.538
[Daharsh] And then you had
Michael Jeffries.

1041
00:56:57.414 --> 00:57:01.126
And it was like he was just there
to have fun on the shoots.

1042
00:57:02.335 --> 00:57:04.712
He-- he very clearly
was into young men too.

1043
00:57:05.296 --> 00:57:08.049
But he was just so weird that--
Who knows what the fuck--

1044
00:57:08.133 --> 00:57:10.218
I don't know what that dude was into.

1045
00:57:10.301 --> 00:57:12.554
It seemed like
they were always implementing.

1046
00:57:13.054 --> 00:57:15.014
like. a new step to the process.

1047
00:57:15.974 --> 00:57:20.979
One of which was
you had to go into. like. this tent

1048
00:57:21.062 --> 00:57:22.564
that was closed off.

1049
00:57:22.647 --> 00:57:26.401
and it was just Bruce. Bruce Weber.
and Michael Jeffries in there.

1050
00:57:27.110 --> 00:57:32.449
Literally. it was an interview for them
to see if they liked your personality.

1051
00:57:32.532 --> 00:57:34.784
who you were.
and what you brought to the table.

1052
00:57:36.077 --> 00:57:40.707
[Berfield] When he ran Abercrombie.
he always sold clothes to women and girls.

1053
00:57:40.790 --> 00:57:44.294
but what I think most people saw

1054
00:57:44.377 --> 00:57:46.421
and. you know. responded to

1055
00:57:46.504 --> 00:57:48.882
was the male image and the male form.

1056
00:57:49.841 --> 00:57:52.594
[Tkacik] I don't even think Mike realized

1057
00:57:52.677 --> 00:57:55.472
that he was also a gay icon.

1058
00:57:56.681 --> 00:58:00.685
It was known or presumed that he was gay.

1059
00:58:01.269 --> 00:58:03.938
but he was very secretive
about his personal life.

1060
00:58:06.191 --> 00:58:08.651
In the early 2000s.

1061
00:58:08.735 --> 00:58:12.197
Mike Jeffries was
still very much closeted.

1062
00:58:13.448 --> 00:58:16.534
[Berfield] Jeffries had been married.
had a son.

1063
00:58:16.618 --> 00:58:18.620
[Tkacik] His wife was mostly
out of the picture.

1064
00:58:18.703 --> 00:58:21.831
and eventually
his life partner. Matthew Smith.

1065
00:58:21.915 --> 00:58:24.501
sort of came on within the company.

1066
00:58:24.584 --> 00:58:29.589
There's a lot that was probably going on
internally with Mike Jeffries

1067
00:58:29.672 --> 00:58:33.009
that very few people
would have been privy to.

1068
00:58:34.385 --> 00:58:38.097
[Abadsidis] He was out of control.
I mean. it was really out of control.

1069
00:58:38.181 --> 00:58:41.893
It was like he had
a bunch of terrible plastic surgeries.

1070
00:58:42.644 --> 00:58:44.062
He wanted to be young.

1071
00:58:44.729 --> 00:58:47.440
He was chasing youth. too. you know?
It's an old story.

1072
00:58:49.526 --> 00:58:52.612
I was fascinated by Mike.
I was fascinated by the company.

1073
00:58:52.695 --> 00:58:59.410
And Mike was just this strange.
bizarre. interesting man.

1074
00:59:00.203 --> 00:59:02.622
I desperately wanted
to write about the company.

1075
00:59:02.705 --> 00:59:04.958
I desperately wanted
to get to their headquarters.

1076
00:59:05.041 --> 00:59:06.042
They called it Campus.

1077
00:59:10.129 --> 00:59:13.967
Then one day. I get a call from an editor
at <i>The New York Times Magazine.</i>

1078
00:59:14.050 --> 00:59:15.969
where I had been writing for a few years.

1079
00:59:16.052 --> 00:59:19.472
and they say. "Do you wanna do a story
about Abercrombie & Fitch?"

1080
00:59:20.056 --> 00:59:23.393
I said. "Absolutely. I'd like to do
this story. How did you get access?"

1081
00:59:23.476 --> 00:59:24.852
They said. "They invited us."

1082
00:59:25.603 --> 00:59:26.854
It's still a question to me

1083
00:59:26.938 --> 00:59:29.274
about why Mike had rejected so many offers

1084
00:59:29.357 --> 00:59:32.735
to write about his brand.
but suddenly I was there.

1085
00:59:34.821 --> 00:59:38.324
He talked about it.
He said. "This is a diva-free zone."

1086
00:59:38.825 --> 00:59:40.201
In a way. <i>he </i>was the diva.

1087
00:59:40.285 --> 00:59:42.787
He was making all of the decisions.

1088
00:59:43.454 --> 00:59:45.873
They had model stores on the campus.

1089
00:59:45.957 --> 00:59:47.292
I watched him walk through

1090
00:59:47.375 --> 00:59:51.796
and obsessively look at how the jeans fell
on every mannequin.

1091
00:59:53.047 --> 00:59:54.507
Going through the store with him

1092
00:59:54.591 --> 01:00:00.930
was revealing of his very clear.
sort of traditional sense

1093
01:00:01.014 --> 01:00:03.016
of masculinity and femininity.

1094
01:00:03.099 --> 01:00:06.311
Saying things like. "We need
to make this dude look more like a dude."

1095
01:00:06.394 --> 01:00:10.064
Uh. for the mannequin.
"We don't want her to look too butch."

1096
01:00:10.148 --> 01:00:11.608
That's exactly what he said.

1097
01:00:12.150 --> 01:00:17.655
He was going through
the racks of Abercrombie girls.

1098
01:00:17.739 --> 01:00:19.782
He picked up a pair of corduroys

1099
01:00:19.866 --> 01:00:22.785
that. I guess to him.
seemed too masculine.

1100
01:00:22.869 --> 01:00:25.913
He said. "Who the fuck
are you designing for?"

1101
01:00:25.997 --> 01:00:27.749
"Dykes on trikes?"

1102
01:00:27.832 --> 01:00:33.296
That language had. um…
went a little beyond. um…

1103
01:00:33.379 --> 01:00:36.007
what was usually implicit.
and became explicit.

1104
01:00:36.090 --> 01:00:40.345
which is that we're not just
designing for men and women.

1105
01:00:40.428 --> 01:00:41.346
girls and boys.

1106
01:00:41.429 --> 01:00:44.932
We're designing
for sexy women and sexy men.

1107
01:00:45.016 --> 01:00:47.685
and sexy girls and sexy boys.

1108
01:00:47.769 --> 01:00:49.771
and sexy meant hetero sexy.

1109
01:00:49.854 --> 01:00:52.231
not "dykes."

1110
01:00:52.315 --> 01:00:55.526
I was really interested
in psychoanalyzing him. [laughs]

1111
01:00:55.610 --> 01:00:58.529
Like. I mean. I wanted to figure out

1112
01:00:59.697 --> 01:01:00.865
who this guy was.

1113
01:01:01.741 --> 01:01:04.535
So I asked him about
all the high-profile controversies.

1114
01:01:04.619 --> 01:01:05.995
the lawsuits.

1115
01:01:06.579 --> 01:01:09.207
and he got incredibly defensive.

1116
01:01:09.290 --> 01:01:11.793
And he ended up saying things that were.

1117
01:01:11.876 --> 01:01:14.379
like. too… too honest.

1118
01:01:14.462 --> 01:01:16.089
[no audio]

1119
01:01:16.172 --> 01:01:19.092
[Denizet-Lewis] He said.
"Are we exclusionary? Absolutely."

1120
01:01:19.175 --> 01:01:22.136
He said.
"Not everyone can wear our clothes."

1121
01:01:22.220 --> 01:01:24.806
"I don't want everyone."
essentially. "wearing our clothes."

1122
01:01:24.889 --> 01:01:27.558
He talked about going after the cool kids.

1123
01:01:27.642 --> 01:01:31.771
He talked about. and again.
this word. the all-American. um. cool kid.

1124
01:01:31.854 --> 01:01:35.483
He sort of fetishized
the all-American boy.

1125
01:01:35.983 --> 01:01:38.736
I mean.
he's not the only person in fashion

1126
01:01:38.820 --> 01:01:41.698
who believed these things.

1127
01:01:41.781 --> 01:01:45.952
but he was the only person.
seemingly. who would say that out loud.

1128
01:01:46.035 --> 01:01:49.455
Two days later.
when I left Ohio. I got an email

1129
01:01:49.539 --> 01:01:53.209
that they were pulling their participation
from the story.

1130
01:01:53.292 --> 01:01:56.587
Which meant. for me. the story was dead
for <i>The New York Times Magazine.</i>

1131
01:01:56.671 --> 01:01:58.673
And I wrote the piece for <i>Salon.</i>

1132
01:01:59.757 --> 01:02:03.010
You know. the piece. when it came out.
got a little bit of attention

1133
01:02:03.094 --> 01:02:08.224
as a profile of this quirky.
highly successful fashion CEO.

1134
01:02:08.307 --> 01:02:10.101
So. in 2006.

1135
01:02:10.184 --> 01:02:13.438
to openly say that
"We're an exclusionary brand"

1136
01:02:13.521 --> 01:02:17.483
apparently was not out of the realm
of things that people would say.

1137
01:02:17.567 --> 01:02:20.027
What makes Abercrombie unique for me

1138
01:02:20.111 --> 01:02:22.488
is that they were unapologetic about it.

1139
01:02:22.572 --> 01:02:24.198
They really went out there.

1140
01:02:24.282 --> 01:02:25.825
They hired certain people.

1141
01:02:25.908 --> 01:02:29.412
They wanted a certain look.
The ads looked a certain way.

1142
01:02:29.495 --> 01:02:31.080
And there wasn't this idea

1143
01:02:31.164 --> 01:02:34.625
that we need to come to the table
around diversity and inclusion

1144
01:02:34.709 --> 01:02:37.712
and make sure
that everyone feels represented.

1145
01:02:37.795 --> 01:02:39.881
They doubled down on being exclusionary.

1146
01:02:39.964 --> 01:02:43.092
They doubled down on saying.
"This is a lifestyle that we're selling."

1147
01:02:43.176 --> 01:02:48.014
"We want our store representatives
to look like the models in our ads."

1148
01:02:48.097 --> 01:02:51.517
"We want this lifestyle
to be associated with us."

1149
01:02:51.601 --> 01:02:56.355
"We're not dissociating
from being discriminating in our taste.

1150
01:02:56.439 --> 01:02:57.356
in our aesthetics."

1151
01:03:01.778 --> 01:03:04.697
One of the reasons
that I didn't wear Abercrombie.

1152
01:03:04.781 --> 01:03:07.200
besides it being incredibly expensive.

1153
01:03:07.283 --> 01:03:09.076
was because I-- I literally couldn't.

1154
01:03:09.160 --> 01:03:10.995
I was the fat. gay. poor kid.

1155
01:03:11.078 --> 01:03:13.539
Pretty much. like. the bullying trifecta.

1156
01:03:13.623 --> 01:03:17.585
So one night I was up late.
and I was just scrolling the Internet.

1157
01:03:17.668 --> 01:03:19.629
The Internet
wasn't as impressive back then.

1158
01:03:19.712 --> 01:03:22.381
It was mostly news.
And I came across this article.

1159
01:03:22.465 --> 01:03:24.842
It was about Mike Jeffries.
I had never heard of him.

1160
01:03:24.926 --> 01:03:26.886
And I read this quote. It says.

1161
01:03:26.969 --> 01:03:31.974
"In every school. there are the cool kids.
and then there are the not-so-cool kids."

1162
01:03:32.058 --> 01:03:34.936
"Candidly. we go after the cool kids."

1163
01:03:35.019 --> 01:03:38.981
"We go after the attractive.
all-American kid with a lot of friends."

1164
01:03:39.065 --> 01:03:40.483
"Are we exclusionary?"

1165
01:03:41.192 --> 01:03:42.485
"Absolutely."

1166
01:03:42.568 --> 01:03:45.530
I found out
that it was actually seven years old.

1167
01:03:45.613 --> 01:03:48.157
That this man had said this
seven years ago.

1168
01:03:48.241 --> 01:03:49.742
and no one did anything about it.

1169
01:03:50.576 --> 01:03:53.996
Someone who had so much power.
Right? Because that's the thing.

1170
01:03:54.080 --> 01:03:56.666
He wasn't just
the CEO of a clothing company.

1171
01:03:57.166 --> 01:03:58.668
He was a creator of cool.

1172
01:04:00.586 --> 01:04:04.215
And so I start this petition
asking Abercrombie & Fitch to apologize

1173
01:04:04.298 --> 01:04:06.801
and to start making plus sizes.

1174
01:04:07.677 --> 01:04:10.680
And eventually. I create a press list.
200 names on it.

1175
01:04:10.763 --> 01:04:13.850
and I send this press release out
to hundreds of people.

1176
01:04:14.350 --> 01:04:15.434
And I go to sleep.

1177
01:04:16.185 --> 01:04:18.145
An interview from. get this. 2006

1178
01:04:18.229 --> 01:04:21.983
with Abercrombie & Fitch CEO Mike Jeffries
has gone viral.

1179
01:04:22.483 --> 01:04:25.653
[reporter 1] <i>If you're looking for</i>
<i>a women's extra-large blouse.</i>

1180
01:04:25.736 --> 01:04:26.612
<i>you're out of luck.</i>

1181
01:04:26.696 --> 01:04:29.949
<i>The trendy retailer CEO</i>
<i>doesn't want your business.</i>

1182
01:04:30.032 --> 01:04:31.367
[reporter 2] He's crossing a line.

1183
01:04:31.450 --> 01:04:33.661
He's crossed the line.
like. a billion times.

1184
01:04:33.744 --> 01:04:35.454
Stop shopping at Abercrombie & Fitch.

1185
01:04:35.538 --> 01:04:37.498
They actually said. "Fat chicks."

1186
01:04:38.374 --> 01:04:41.377
[Tkacik] <i>It shows up on Twitter.</i>
<i>and suddenly it goes viral.</i>

1187
01:04:41.460 --> 01:04:45.715
<i>and there's this huge campaign</i>
<i>to oust Mike Jeffries.</i>

1188
01:04:46.340 --> 01:04:48.175
Bitch! Your ass would do some good

1189
01:04:48.259 --> 01:04:50.803
if Kim Kardashian could squeeze
her big butt into your clothes.

1190
01:04:50.887 --> 01:04:53.973
This guy is not attractive.
He's an old hag.

1191
01:04:54.056 --> 01:04:56.475
Abercrombie & Fitch
is one of the most racist places

1192
01:04:56.559 --> 01:04:57.602
I've ever been to.

1193
01:04:57.685 --> 01:04:59.478
They suck inside and out.

1194
01:04:59.562 --> 01:05:01.647
And their clothes are overpriced.

1195
01:05:01.731 --> 01:05:04.817
Regardless of whether
your T-shirts fit these tits.

1196
01:05:05.610 --> 01:05:07.194
I'm not gonna shop in your store.

1197
01:05:07.278 --> 01:05:09.697
[reporter 3] He says that if companies
try to target all sizes.

1198
01:05:09.780 --> 01:05:10.740
they end up in trouble.

1199
01:05:10.823 --> 01:05:13.159
and if you don't alienate anyone.
you don't excite anyone.

1200
01:05:13.659 --> 01:05:16.037
-Let's take a look at him again.
-[both laughing]

1201
01:05:17.455 --> 01:05:21.709
[girl] If you're judging someone on
how cool they are just by looking at them.

1202
01:05:21.792 --> 01:05:24.003
and if you're hiring
only good-looking people.

1203
01:05:24.086 --> 01:05:25.630
how about hiring good workers?

1204
01:05:26.255 --> 01:05:29.133
[Denizet-Lewis] I interviewed a girl
who had led one of the boycotts.

1205
01:05:29.216 --> 01:05:33.304
and she said. "Abercrombie has
the biggest impact on people my age."

1206
01:05:33.387 --> 01:05:36.807
Girls think that
they need to be incredibly thin.

1207
01:05:36.891 --> 01:05:40.770
Boys think they need to be
this-- this sort of jacked image

1208
01:05:40.853 --> 01:05:44.273
that they see when they walk in the stores
and on their advertisements.

1209
01:05:44.357 --> 01:05:47.610
She said to me that
there was no brand for her and her friends

1210
01:05:47.693 --> 01:05:49.195
that was more influential.

1211
01:05:49.278 --> 01:05:51.489
In high school. I suffered with anorexia.

1212
01:05:51.572 --> 01:05:54.909
and so I knew
just how harmful that words like that

1213
01:05:54.992 --> 01:05:57.828
and rhetoric like that could be
on the psyche of young people.

1214
01:05:57.912 --> 01:06:00.665
And that's who
they were talking to. right?

1215
01:06:00.748 --> 01:06:02.750
That's who their consumers were.

1216
01:06:02.833 --> 01:06:06.045
They were telling young people
that if they didn't look a certain way.

1217
01:06:06.128 --> 01:06:08.172
if they weren't a certain type of person.

1218
01:06:08.255 --> 01:06:10.466
that they didn't belong in their clothing.

1219
01:06:10.549 --> 01:06:13.511
This was weeks and weeks and weeks

1220
01:06:13.594 --> 01:06:15.972
that people were talking about this.
covering this.

1221
01:06:16.055 --> 01:06:18.474
That's when we get the call
from Abercrombie & Fitch

1222
01:06:18.557 --> 01:06:21.602
saying. like.
"Hey. do you wanna come to Ohio

1223
01:06:21.686 --> 01:06:23.771
and. you know. help us out?"

1224
01:06:23.854 --> 01:06:25.648
"Help us see if we can work past this."

1225
01:06:25.731 --> 01:06:28.234
"See if we can
come to some kind of agreement."

1226
01:06:28.317 --> 01:06:32.488
It's myself. the CEO of
the National Eating Disorders Association.

1227
01:06:32.571 --> 01:06:34.323
a campaigner from Change.org.

1228
01:06:34.407 --> 01:06:37.535
and two other
sort of eating disorders professionals.

1229
01:06:37.618 --> 01:06:42.415
And I went on to talk to them
about not just size-based discrimination.

1230
01:06:42.498 --> 01:06:43.708
why discrimination is bad.

1231
01:06:43.791 --> 01:06:48.170
I talked to them about why it was
actually just a stupid business decision.

1232
01:06:48.254 --> 01:06:52.842
When 60% of your consumer base
is wearing these plus sizes.

1233
01:06:52.925 --> 01:06:54.510
why aren't you embracing them?

1234
01:06:55.011 --> 01:06:56.595
[O'Keefe] And then the team comes in.

1235
01:06:56.679 --> 01:07:00.725
and they're smiling.
and they're bubbly. and they're white.

1236
01:07:00.808 --> 01:07:02.268
except for one person.

1237
01:07:02.351 --> 01:07:04.937
the Chief Diversity Officer.

1238
01:07:05.021 --> 01:07:06.564
Of course. he was a Black man.

1239
01:07:06.647 --> 01:07:08.733
[producer] "We go after the cool kids."

1240
01:07:09.316 --> 01:07:11.777
What did you think when Mike said that?

1241
01:07:12.486 --> 01:07:13.863
Um…

1242
01:07:13.946 --> 01:07:15.865
I have to respectfully decline on that.

1243
01:07:15.948 --> 01:07:20.995
You-- you would not be wrong
about how you think I felt about that.

1244
01:07:21.078 --> 01:07:22.038
I mean…

1245
01:07:22.121 --> 01:07:25.166
So we're sitting at this board table.
this long boardroom table.

1246
01:07:25.249 --> 01:07:29.211
and I say. "Wait a minute.
Where's Mike? Where's Mike Jeffries?"

1247
01:07:29.295 --> 01:07:32.006
Mike Jeffries did not show up
to the meeting.

1248
01:07:32.798 --> 01:07:37.595
And so I start taking out stacks
of our 2.000 pages of petitions.

1249
01:07:37.678 --> 01:07:39.847
He had a box of stuff.
Like. what's the box for?

1250
01:07:40.347 --> 01:07:44.852
And I plop them down
in front of each executive dramatically.

1251
01:07:44.935 --> 01:07:45.853
really dramatically.

1252
01:07:45.936 --> 01:07:46.937
And I said…

1253
01:07:48.230 --> 01:07:51.150
"Each one of these piles of petitions

1254
01:07:51.233 --> 01:07:53.611
represents thousands of people

1255
01:07:53.694 --> 01:07:56.489
who are against
what you are doing as a brand."

1256
01:07:56.572 --> 01:07:59.408
Their Chief Diversity Officer
looked pretty offended.

1257
01:07:59.492 --> 01:08:00.951
He pulled out this little book.

1258
01:08:01.035 --> 01:08:05.831
He tried to explain to me how. actually.
they were an incredibly diverse company.

1259
01:08:05.915 --> 01:08:08.959
and all of the great things
that they had done for diversity

1260
01:08:09.043 --> 01:08:11.045
in their stores since he had come on.

1261
01:08:11.128 --> 01:08:12.463
And so he hands me this book.

1262
01:08:12.546 --> 01:08:15.382
and I sort of look at it.
and I throw it back at him.

1263
01:08:15.466 --> 01:08:17.426
"So this means nothing.
Look in this room."

1264
01:08:17.510 --> 01:08:19.303
"You're the only person of color here."

1265
01:08:19.386 --> 01:08:23.474
The higher up you go.
the older it gets and the whiter it gets.

1266
01:08:23.557 --> 01:08:25.935
These people were there very early on.

1267
01:08:26.018 --> 01:08:29.563
They're telling you who looks Abercrombie.

1268
01:08:31.190 --> 01:08:34.276
[Givhan] Yeah. you've got
the numbers at the store level.

1269
01:08:34.360 --> 01:08:37.571
but what about
at the vice president level.

1270
01:08:37.655 --> 01:08:41.951
and what about the people
who sit on your board of directors?

1271
01:08:42.034 --> 01:08:44.787
That becomes a question of the system.

1272
01:08:44.870 --> 01:08:48.165
and that becomes one
that's much more challenging.

1273
01:08:48.249 --> 01:08:50.668
It's not something that can be fixed

1274
01:08:50.751 --> 01:08:54.463
with a hiring binge. you know.
over the course of a year.

1275
01:08:54.547 --> 01:08:57.007
Upper management stayed white.

1276
01:08:57.091 --> 01:09:00.177
Most of the concerns in the decree
were from the store side.

1277
01:09:00.261 --> 01:09:03.514
[Corley] I mean. again.
they were 90% of your employee population.

1278
01:09:03.597 --> 01:09:05.724
So that was largely what we focused on.

1279
01:09:06.684 --> 01:09:12.148
You could call it a-- a glass ceiling
for all people of color.

1280
01:09:12.231 --> 01:09:16.402
You go to the office.
you see the new crop of regional managers.

1281
01:09:16.485 --> 01:09:18.696
was like. "Anybody? Anybody?"

1282
01:09:18.779 --> 01:09:19.780
"Okay. no."

1283
01:09:20.364 --> 01:09:24.118
I would be doing all the managers of color
that I worked with over the years

1284
01:09:24.201 --> 01:09:27.121
that I truly appreciated a disservice

1285
01:09:27.204 --> 01:09:28.956
if I didn't at least say that

1286
01:09:29.832 --> 01:09:32.334
it wasn't <i>not </i>racist.

1287
01:09:33.669 --> 01:09:35.379
[producer laughs] "It wasn't not racist"!

1288
01:09:35.462 --> 01:09:36.338
[both laugh]

1289
01:09:36.422 --> 01:09:41.719
I think the real evidence
of the leadership commitment came to light

1290
01:09:41.802 --> 01:09:43.387
when the consent decree ended.

1291
01:09:43.470 --> 01:09:47.766
They definitely improved
a great deal on the surface.

1292
01:09:47.850 --> 01:09:51.604
But they didn't get anywhere close
to what they sort of promised they would.

1293
01:09:51.687 --> 01:09:54.982
and none of this was binding.
and that's the-- that's the big problem.

1294
01:10:07.745 --> 01:10:09.413
[Spencer] When the consent decree ended.

1295
01:10:09.496 --> 01:10:12.958
you started to see
what you call "the fatigue."

1296
01:10:13.042 --> 01:10:15.127
Right? People were like… [sighs]

1297
01:10:15.628 --> 01:10:17.546
Then you start experiencing
the resistance.

1298
01:10:17.630 --> 01:10:19.131
"Do we really have to do this?"

1299
01:10:19.215 --> 01:10:22.176
"Do we really need to allocate
this much money to that?" Right?

1300
01:10:22.259 --> 01:10:23.219
And so…

1301
01:10:24.511 --> 01:10:26.013
were we really committed?

1302
01:10:26.680 --> 01:10:27.640
Or not?

1303
01:10:27.723 --> 01:10:29.850
I've been in Todd's seat.

1304
01:10:29.934 --> 01:10:31.977
That is an incredibly tough place to be

1305
01:10:32.061 --> 01:10:35.439
that we put marginalized people in
all the time.

1306
01:10:35.522 --> 01:10:38.234
And we say. "Okay. fix all the problems."

1307
01:10:38.317 --> 01:10:42.780
He was set up to fail.
and I think that's why he ultimately left.

1308
01:10:43.739 --> 01:10:47.576
Well. I've always been cautious
about how I talk about my experience

1309
01:10:47.660 --> 01:10:48.911
'cause when I left.

1310
01:10:48.994 --> 01:10:52.665
I mean. uh. the place doesn't look
like it did when I inherited it.

1311
01:10:52.748 --> 01:10:54.041
And if nothing else.

1312
01:10:54.792 --> 01:10:56.252
that. to me. is success.

1313
01:11:01.048 --> 01:11:02.049
Okay.

1314
01:11:07.846 --> 01:11:09.390
I'm Samantha Elauf.

1315
01:11:10.057 --> 01:11:12.476
I was born and raised in Tulsa. Oklahoma.

1316
01:11:12.977 --> 01:11:16.021
So I was applying for Abercrombie & Fitch.

1317
01:11:16.105 --> 01:11:18.899
There was one question that they asked.
which is funny now.

1318
01:11:18.983 --> 01:11:20.985
but as a minority. it stood out to me.

1319
01:11:21.068 --> 01:11:23.737
and it was.
"What does diversity mean to you?"

1320
01:11:24.321 --> 01:11:27.157
So I was like.
"Okay. I'll fit in perfect."

1321
01:11:27.241 --> 01:11:29.451
At the interview.
I was also wearing jeans.

1322
01:11:29.535 --> 01:11:31.287
I think I was wearing a white basic.

1323
01:11:31.370 --> 01:11:34.373
and I was wearing a black scarf.
traditionally worn.

1324
01:11:35.040 --> 01:11:37.209
After the interview.
she told me she'd let me know

1325
01:11:37.293 --> 01:11:38.627
when to come in for orientation.

1326
01:11:39.586 --> 01:11:42.131
And I remember
my friend messaging me and being like.

1327
01:11:42.214 --> 01:11:44.842
"Did my manager call you yet?
When's your orientation?"

1328
01:11:44.925 --> 01:11:48.345
I was like. "She hasn't called me yet."
and she's like. "I will ask her."

1329
01:11:49.305 --> 01:11:52.683
Whenever she asked the manager.
the manager was acting very strange.

1330
01:11:53.559 --> 01:11:56.312
After she interviewed me.
she called the district manager

1331
01:11:56.395 --> 01:11:58.355
because I was wearing a black headscarf.

1332
01:11:58.856 --> 01:12:01.567
At the time. they had a no-black policy.

1333
01:12:02.234 --> 01:12:05.779
He told her. "It doesn't matter
what color she wore. She can't work here."

1334
01:12:07.781 --> 01:12:08.949
I didn't know what to think.

1335
01:12:09.033 --> 01:12:11.452
That was the first time
anything had happened to me like that.

1336
01:12:11.535 --> 01:12:13.871
Soon after.
I was at my mom's friend's house.

1337
01:12:13.954 --> 01:12:16.206
and I was telling her what happened.

1338
01:12:16.290 --> 01:12:20.711
and she communicated with me
that I should get in touch with CAIR.

1339
01:12:20.794 --> 01:12:24.006
Council of American-Islamic Relations.

1340
01:12:24.590 --> 01:12:28.510
After getting into contact with them.
they made my story public.

1341
01:12:30.179 --> 01:12:33.349
They decided to file my case with the EOC

1342
01:12:33.432 --> 01:12:35.976
and see if they would take it on
as a lawsuit.

1343
01:12:36.810 --> 01:12:40.314
And that's when it got real. honestly.

1344
01:12:42.524 --> 01:12:43.942
My picture was everywhere.

1345
01:12:44.026 --> 01:12:46.278
and people were. like.
sending me messages.

1346
01:12:46.779 --> 01:12:49.365
People were tweeting the craziest things.

1347
01:12:50.407 --> 01:12:53.202
There was a point
where I stopped reading any comments.

1348
01:12:53.702 --> 01:12:58.457
For every positive. encouraging words.
I was getting so much hate.

1349
01:13:00.292 --> 01:13:02.294
I did get a couple death threats.

1350
01:13:03.587 --> 01:13:06.256
It was more. like.
hate towards my religion

1351
01:13:06.924 --> 01:13:09.676
and my beliefs to choose to cover.

1352
01:13:10.177 --> 01:13:13.305
But at the same time.
I even had Muslims. like. say.

1353
01:13:14.014 --> 01:13:16.308
"Why would you wanna
work for Abercrombie?"

1354
01:13:18.268 --> 01:13:21.146
I also had people say.
"Go back to your country."

1355
01:13:21.230 --> 01:13:24.441
which is funny because I was born
and raised in Tulsa. Oklahoma.

1356
01:13:24.525 --> 01:13:25.776
Where am I supposed to go?

1357
01:13:27.861 --> 01:13:31.990
[Maheshwari] Abercrombie really
dug its heels in on this topic

1358
01:13:32.074 --> 01:13:33.784
and decided that they were right.

1359
01:13:33.867 --> 01:13:37.413
The Abercrombie lawyers
tried to compare this to. you know.

1360
01:13:37.496 --> 01:13:38.747
wearing a baseball hat

1361
01:13:38.831 --> 01:13:42.334
and saying. "Well. we wouldn't let
an employee wear a baseball cap."

1362
01:13:42.418 --> 01:13:44.545
But obviously.
there's a really big difference

1363
01:13:44.628 --> 01:13:47.339
between a hijab and a baseball cap.

1364
01:13:47.423 --> 01:13:51.260
I remember going to my phone.
and it was. like. blowing up.

1365
01:13:52.761 --> 01:13:56.140
The Supreme Court came out with a list
of the 100 cases they would hear.

1366
01:13:56.223 --> 01:13:57.891
and mine was one of them.

1367
01:13:57.975 --> 01:13:59.685
[Berfield] That was pretty significant.

1368
01:13:59.768 --> 01:14:03.856
First. that a company would allow a case
to go to the Supreme Court.

1369
01:14:03.939 --> 01:14:05.232
Very unusual.

1370
01:14:05.315 --> 01:14:08.110
Most companies would want to settle

1371
01:14:08.193 --> 01:14:12.322
because they would be scared
about the publicity. winning or losing.

1372
01:14:12.406 --> 01:14:16.201
Their argument was that if they hired me.
I would hurt their brand.

1373
01:14:16.285 --> 01:14:18.370
which in return would hurt their sales.

1374
01:14:18.454 --> 01:14:21.039
That was their argument.
that I would hurt their numbers

1375
01:14:21.123 --> 01:14:22.958
because I didn't fit their look policy.

1376
01:14:24.126 --> 01:14:25.294
[reporter 4] <i>The Supreme Court</i>

1377
01:14:25.377 --> 01:14:28.172
<i>rejected that argument</i>
<i>by an eight to one vote.</i>

1378
01:14:29.047 --> 01:14:31.633
[reporter 5] <i>The justices say</i>
<i>Abercrombie & Fitch's actions</i>

1379
01:14:31.717 --> 01:14:34.761
<i>violated the Civil Rights Act of 1964.</i>

1380
01:14:36.430 --> 01:14:38.932
[Sagafi] If Justice Scalia is moved
to say you're discriminating.

1381
01:14:39.016 --> 01:14:40.434
you're really doing something wrong.

1382
01:14:41.310 --> 01:14:44.855
I had eight that voted in my favor.
and I had one who didn't.

1383
01:14:44.938 --> 01:14:49.485
and the one judge who did not vote
in my favor was African American.

1384
01:14:49.568 --> 01:14:51.904
So. not saying
'cause you're African American.

1385
01:14:51.987 --> 01:14:55.574
you have to be on my side.
because we're different.

1386
01:14:55.657 --> 01:14:57.284
but I was just surprised.

1387
01:14:58.911 --> 01:15:02.164
To this day. when people are like.
"I saw you in my history book."

1388
01:15:02.247 --> 01:15:04.041
or. "Oh. I was reading about you."

1389
01:15:04.124 --> 01:15:06.960
"Oh. I'm studying law.
We talked about you."

1390
01:15:07.044 --> 01:15:10.214
I don't think I realized.
like. what all I did.

1391
01:15:13.467 --> 01:15:16.220
[O'Keefe] Abercrombie & Fitch went
all the way to the Supreme Court.

1392
01:15:16.303 --> 01:15:19.014
Discrimination was not just a blip.

1393
01:15:19.097 --> 01:15:21.058
It was not just one quote
from seven years.

1394
01:15:21.141 --> 01:15:23.435
It was their brand. It was their identity.

1395
01:15:23.519 --> 01:15:27.189
They rooted themselves in discrimination
at every single level.

1396
01:15:28.065 --> 01:15:30.859
Abercrombie. at that point.
was almost synonymous with scandal.

1397
01:15:30.943 --> 01:15:32.694
It wasn't really about the clothing

1398
01:15:32.778 --> 01:15:35.864
or that they had too much logo.
and logo was going out of style.

1399
01:15:35.948 --> 01:15:38.992
It was really like.
"Oh. this brand is becoming problematic."

1400
01:15:39.076 --> 01:15:41.620
because. as analysts would say.

1401
01:15:41.703 --> 01:15:45.415
all of this is distracting from
the business of selling clothes.

1402
01:15:47.834 --> 01:15:51.964
<i>The second quarter proved</i>
<i>to be more difficult than expected.</i>

1403
01:15:52.047 --> 01:15:54.967
<i>We are not satisfied with our results</i>

1404
01:15:55.050 --> 01:16:00.556
<i>and are working hard to improve the trend</i>
<i>for the third quarter and beyond.</i>

1405
01:16:03.559 --> 01:16:07.854
[Berfield] Abercrombie was becoming
irrelevant under Mike Jeffries.

1406
01:16:08.355 --> 01:16:11.275
But Mike Jeffries
is making a lot of money.

1407
01:16:12.234 --> 01:16:15.237
Mike's been hounded
by these shareholder lawsuits saying.

1408
01:16:15.320 --> 01:16:18.991
"Why are you paying yourself
$40 million a year

1409
01:16:19.074 --> 01:16:23.287
when your stock is. you know.
in the. like. bottom 10%?"

1410
01:16:23.370 --> 01:16:25.622
I actually found a manual

1411
01:16:25.706 --> 01:16:29.668
for how to treat Mike Jeffries
on the company airplane.

1412
01:16:29.751 --> 01:16:31.295
[female voice] <i>Aircraft standards.</i>

1413
01:16:32.296 --> 01:16:37.342
<i>A 47-page manual</i>
<i>for the Abercrombie & Fitch executive jet.</i>

1414
01:16:37.426 --> 01:16:42.139
It's impossible to overstate
how particular

1415
01:16:42.222 --> 01:16:43.807
the instructions were.

1416
01:16:43.890 --> 01:16:46.643
[female voice]
<i>If the passengers are eating cold food.</i>

1417
01:16:46.727 --> 01:16:49.605
<i>crew members are not to eat hot meals.</i>

1418
01:16:49.688 --> 01:16:50.981
The kind of instructions

1419
01:16:51.064 --> 01:16:54.234
that you never really see
revealed to the public.

1420
01:16:54.860 --> 01:16:57.696
[female voice]
<i>When Michael or a guest make a request.</i>

1421
01:16:57.779 --> 01:16:59.323
<i>respond by saying.</i>

1422
01:17:00.032 --> 01:17:00.949
<i>"No problem."</i>

1423
01:17:01.533 --> 01:17:06.580
<i>This should be used in place of phrases</i>
<i>like. "Sure." or. "Just a minute."</i>

1424
01:17:08.081 --> 01:17:11.668
The shifts he made
for the company were great

1425
01:17:11.752 --> 01:17:14.379
in terms of a small period of time.

1426
01:17:14.463 --> 01:17:16.506
I don't think any of that was sustainable.

1427
01:17:16.590 --> 01:17:19.468
It didn't feel like
there was a long-term strategy there.

1428
01:17:19.551 --> 01:17:23.805
It felt like it was. "Let's grow it
as big as it can possibly get

1429
01:17:23.889 --> 01:17:25.057
and see what happens."

1430
01:17:25.140 --> 01:17:28.435
You don't want your brand
to run white-hot.

1431
01:17:28.518 --> 01:17:32.147
because white-hot brands always burn out.

1432
01:17:33.815 --> 01:17:36.193
[reporter 8] Abercrombie.
it's in dire straits.

1433
01:17:36.693 --> 01:17:39.237
It's just that CEO Mike Jeffries
doesn't seem to know it.

1434
01:17:40.364 --> 01:17:43.867
[Rupp] In the 2000s. business started
to really change for Abercrombie.

1435
01:17:44.701 --> 01:17:46.620
and I think the customer began to change.

1436
01:17:48.246 --> 01:17:51.750
[Maheshwari] It was losing
its luster with teens.

1437
01:17:55.879 --> 01:17:57.255
[Sanchez] It wasn't cool.

1438
01:17:57.339 --> 01:18:01.968
You were wearing Abercrombie & Fitch.
it was like a construction outfit.

1439
01:18:02.052 --> 01:18:05.013
When you're in construction.
you put on your boots to go to work.

1440
01:18:05.097 --> 01:18:08.600
and you get home.
those boots and all that stuff comes out.

1441
01:18:08.684 --> 01:18:09.810
You go to the shower.

1442
01:18:09.893 --> 01:18:13.230
You're wearin' somethin' else
to do whatever you're gonna do after that.

1443
01:18:13.313 --> 01:18:15.774
That was our Abercrombie & Fitch clothing.

1444
01:18:15.857 --> 01:18:19.319
At some point. those kids that learned
it wasn't cool to be bullied grew up

1445
01:18:19.403 --> 01:18:22.864
and decided they didn't wanna spend money
at a place that made them feel bad.

1446
01:18:22.948 --> 01:18:25.409
And so Abercrombie & Fitch. like…

1447
01:18:26.118 --> 01:18:28.036
Some of that aura went away

1448
01:18:28.120 --> 01:18:33.875
precisely because exclusion
was the root of their success.

1449
01:18:34.751 --> 01:18:39.423
And exclusion itself
stopped being quite so cool.

1450
01:18:40.757 --> 01:18:42.801
We've got breaking news
on the retail front.

1451
01:18:42.884 --> 01:18:46.388
Abercrombie & Fitch.
the CEO is stepping down.

1452
01:18:48.974 --> 01:18:54.438
He literally was on the phone
with executives on Sunday. December 7th.

1453
01:18:55.147 --> 01:18:57.983
and Monday. December 8th.
did not show up for work.

1454
01:18:58.066 --> 01:18:59.234
Never showed up again.

1455
01:18:59.317 --> 01:19:02.362
and many people
have never seen him since then.

1456
01:19:04.865 --> 01:19:08.452
[Spencer] I think people thought
that Mike was a permanent fixture.

1457
01:19:08.535 --> 01:19:10.454
and you sit there and you think.

1458
01:19:10.537 --> 01:19:14.833
"How long will there be tolerance
for this sort of behavior.

1459
01:19:14.916 --> 01:19:17.586
this type of comment.
this type of leadership?"

1460
01:19:17.669 --> 01:19:19.588
So you think he would never go away.

1461
01:19:19.671 --> 01:19:22.340
So I remember thinking when he finally--

1462
01:19:22.424 --> 01:19:24.885
[laughs] I was like. "Wow!"

1463
01:19:24.968 --> 01:19:27.095
Like. "They finally got rid of him."

1464
01:19:27.596 --> 01:19:30.891
At some point.
you know. all things come to an end.

1465
